<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hata: Need for Gradual Dialogue With DPRK </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2002131394 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 19 Feb 
94 Evening Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2002131394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tsutomu Hata, deputy prime minister and 
concurrently foreign minister, appeared on a live program of 
Tokai Television on the morning of 19 February. In the program, 
he touched on how Japan should deal with the DPRK's (North 
Korea's) suspected possession of nuclear arms in its diplomacy 
toward the country. He stressed: "It is important that the 
United States, Japan, and the ROK will get united in dialogue 
with the country gradually and step by step." He also added: 
"Because some members of the ruling coalition parties have had 
close relations with North Korea, it would be possible to hold 
dialogue with the country via them." Thus, he indicated that 
the ruling parties would also seek dialogue with North Korea 
through diplomatic efforts with the Social Democratic Party of 
Japan and other parties playing a mediatory role. 

</TEXT>

