<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Lack of Business Effort by U.S. Firms Alleged </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1902115494 Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 19 Feb 94 
Morning Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1902115494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa made a speech at 
his meeting with lawmakers held at the Japan New Party's 
headquarters in Takanawa in Tokyo on the evening of 18 February 
and said: "Probably, Japan and the United States never before 
had such intensive discussions at summit meetings." In this 
way, he stressed that Japan held fast to its stand at the recent 
Japan-U.S. summit talk. 
  As an example, he cited the following dialogue: President 
Clinton insisted on saying that "although both countries signed 
more than 30 accords after the 1970's, none of them was 
observed." In response, the prime minister said: "I do not 
think what you have said is right. Nippon Telegraph and 
Telephone [NTT] Company purchased $17-million-worth of goods in 
1980. But, the NTT is buying $780-million-worth of goods now. 
This is an increase by 46 times. Can you still say that no 
progress has been made?" 
  Moreover, Hosokawa also touched on the issue of auto and 
auto 
parts, which was a focal point at the new economic talks, and 
said: "Cars with a steering wheel on the right-hand side are 
driven in 18 percent of the countries in the world. There are 
many European cars, such as Mercedes and BMW's, in the Japanese 
market. Since U.S. companies are not trying hard to sell their 
cars in Japan, it is not right for you to say we are not buying 
U.S. cars." Reportedly, Hosokawa pointed out lack of efforts by 
the United States. 

</TEXT>

