<H3> <TI>   Hosokawa, Business Leaders Discuss U.S. Ties </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2102025794 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 20 
February 94 Morning Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2102025794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] On the afternoon of 19 February, Prime Minister 
Morihiro Hosokawa invited business leaders who had attended the 
recent Conference of Japanese and American Businessmen [CJAB], 
including Yotaro Kobayashi, president of Fuji-Xerox and CJAB 
acting chairman, to his official residence, and held intimate 
talks on Japan-U.S. economic relations for about 90 minutes. 
  While reporting to the prime minister on details of the 
conference, Kobayashi and other business leaders indicated their 
views that with the upturn in the U.S. economy, the repulsion 
for Japan that had existed in American industrial circles was 
gradually weakening. 
  After the meeting, Kobayashi and other businessmen stressed: 
"In the United States, the atmosphere is entirely different at 
the governmental and private-sector levels. It is not so 
intensified at the private-sector level." They disclosed that 
in their report to the prime minister on the details of the 
CJAB, they had stressed this belief. 

</TEXT>

