<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ozawa on Need for Nonbinding `Effort Targets' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2302114994 Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 23 Feb 94 
Morning Edition p 1 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2302114994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Speaking with foreign correspondents in Tokyo on 22 
February, Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party] Secretary General 
Ichiro Ozawa referred to the issue of setting numerical targets 
over which the Japan-U.S. summit blew up. He said that Japan 
should set up "effort targets" on condition that "failure in 
achieving such targets should not be subject to sanctions," thus 
showing a flexible attitude toward setting up some kind of 
numerical figures to measure progress in opening the Japanese 
market. This has been reported by news agencies. Since Mr. 
Ozawa was deeply involved in past Japan-U.S. negotiations on 
economic issues, his remarks have invited negative reactions 
from those concerned with negotiations saying: "Since term 
`targets' will be taken as a pledge, numerical targets should 
not be set." 
  In dispatching reports on Ozawa's remarks, such news 
agencies 
as the AP News Agency and KNIGHT-RIDDER NEWSPAPERS INC used the 
term "targets." According to their dispatches and participants 
of Ozawa's meeting with foreign correspondents, Mr. Ozawa 
reportedly said that: "Japan and the United States should make 
mutual efforts while keeping mutual reliance. It is good for 
Japan to set up targets for Japan's effort to promote market 
opening if the targets are not subject to sanctions." Moreover, 
he reportedly said that the Japan-U.S. economic framework talks 
"should be concluded by the end of March," thus showing 
confidence in settling the issue at an early date. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

