<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Vice Ministers Urge Domestic Demand Expansion </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1802135594 Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 18 Feb 94 
Evening Edition p 1 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1802135594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Parliamentary vice ministers of the government met 
on the morning of 17 February at the prime minister's official 
residence. During the meeting, Itsusei Koga, parliamentary vice 
minister of the Economic Planning Agency, referred to the 
drastic appreciation of the yen against the U.S. dollar 
following the breakdown of the Japanese-U.S. framework talks and 
said, "The government needs to formulate clearer plans to expand 
domestic demand." During the meeting, one parliamentary vice 
minister after another also voiced the need for the government 
to quickly take steps to deal with the steep rise in the yen's 
value against the U.S. dollar. 
  Commenting on the impact of the recent sharp rise in the 
value of the yen against the U.S. dollar, Eisei Ito, 
parliamentary vice minister of the Construction Ministry, said, 
"I have no intention of raising questions about the outcome of 
the recent Japanese-U.S. summit talks, but if the government 
fails to deal properly with the drastic appreciation of the yen, 
the package of stimulus measures compiled recently by the 
government would have little effect in stimulating the economy." 
  At the meeting, Toshi Masuda, parliamentary vice minister of 
the National Land Agency, stated: "The government should make 
public its plans to deal with the recent steep rise in the yen's 
value in a way so that other nations can easily understand them. 
All government officials should realize the need to reform the 
structure of Japan's economy." In this way, he called for a 
change in economic policy in order to convert Japan's economy 
into an economy driven by domestic demand. 
  In connection with the issue of opening the Japanese 
mobile-phone market, the U.S. Government is poised to slap 
sanctions on Japan after confirming "Japan's violation of a 
Japanese-U.S. agreement." In commenting on the move by the U.S. 
Government, Aogu Matsumae, parliamentary vice minister of the 
Posts and Telecommunications Ministry, criticized the U.S. 
Government for taking such a step, saying, "The assertion by the 
U.S. Government is unreasonable, and the Japanese Government 
cannot go along with the request from the U.S. Government." 

</TEXT>

