Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  23 February 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hosokawa on Need To Review Basic 
Defense Policy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2202110994 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 22 Feb 
94 Morning Edition p 1 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2202110994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] During a House of Representatives Budget Committee 
meeting on the afternoon of 21 February, Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa referred to the issue of reviewing the "National 
Defense Program Guidelines" (which were endorsed by the cabinet 
in 1976). He said: "It has been almost 20 years since the 
concept of basic defense power was formulated (since the present 
defense program guidelines were drawn up). I think it is 
necessary to rethink basic defense power in a way that is 
relative for this new era. We should basically change our 
viewpoints in the present vast flow." In this way, Hosokawa 
clarified his plan to drastically review the "concept of basic 
defense power," which is the basis of the present defense 
buildup program. Hosokawa was answering a question by Sohei 
Miyashita (a member of the Liberal Democratic Party). 
  Basic defense power is stipulated as the minimum defense 
capability that Japan, as an independent state, should maintain 
in peace time. It has been explained that "basic defense power 
is not something that directly confronts possible military 
threats imposed on Japan." Hosokawa's remarks in the session 
will likely create a great stir because they note the need for 
drastically reviewing the National Defense Prorgram Guidelines, 
including the "basic concept" of the defense buildup, and they 
are not in line with explanations given by former governments. 
  Hosokawa also indicated the intention to have his private 
consultative body come to a conclusion on new defense program 
guidelines as early as this summer, and expressed the hope that 
"the conclusion will be reflected in some way in the defense 
buildup for fiscal 1995." However, Kazuo Aichi, director 
general of the Defense Agency, advanced an opinion differing 
from Hosokawa's. He said: "In view of the actual situation, it 
will be very difficult to completely change the defense program 
in the fiscal 1995 budget." 
  LDP's Miyashita also asked a question regarding the issue of 
how participation by the Self-Defense Forces [SDF] in UN 
peacekeeping operations (PKO) should be evaluated in the SDF's 
duties. He said: "There is an opinion that Article 3 of the SDF 
Law should be amended to rank PKO missions as the SDF's main 
duty. What do you think of this?" In reply, Hosokawa said: 
"The government should bring this issue before the people 
first. After the people have fully discussed the matter, the 
government should begin to study it." In this way, he indicated 
the intention to handle the issue carefully. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

