<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kumagai on Clinton's `Irritation' Over Trade </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1902105494 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 18 Feb 
94 Evening Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1902105494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] President Clinton has cited the Japanese 
bureaucracy as standing in the way of opening the Japanese 
market and criticized the Ministry of International Trade and 
Industry by name. Commenting on the President's remarks at a 
news conference on 18 February after a cabinet session, Hiroshi 
Kumagai, minister of the international trade and industry, said: 
"American negotiators have often criticized the Japanese 
bureaucracy at the Japan-U.S. economic framework talks, but 
their criticism stems from misunderstanding. Japan's huge trade 
surplus with the United States has long continued unabated. We 
have to understand the President's irritation and to work to 
reduce Japan's current account surplus." 
  At the news conference, the minister also said: "We do not 
mean that Japan cannot reduce its trade surplus with the United 
States and Japan should work to do voluntarily what it can do 
for the reduction of its trade surplus. I am convinced that the 
private sector is thinking of measures to reduce it." In this 
way, Minister Kumagai stressed the need for the private sector 
to make its own independent effort to break the current impasse 
in the Japan-U.S. relations. 

</TEXT>

