<F P=100> AUSTRALASIA </F>
<F P=101> Australia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Evans: Russian Spying Not Considered `Crisis' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2402101894 Melbourne Radio Australia in English 0900 GMT 
24 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2402101894 </F>
<F P=104>  Melbourne Radio Australia </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Australian Government says six Russian diplomats 
caught spying were allowed to leave Australia during the second 
half of last year. The foreign minister, Gareth Evans, said the 
Russian diplomats left between July and December. He said the 
spies had been discovered during an investigation by ASIO, the 
Australian Security Intelligence Organization. Senator Evans 
said the espionage did not constitute a security crisis of any 
kind or any significant rupture in relations with Russia. 
  [Begin Evans recording] The kind of role they might have had 
in the past is not one that's appropriate to the new Russia, 
after the end of the Cold War. And there has of course been a 
very significant downgrading of the Russian espionage 
establishment since the end of the Cold War, and I think there's 
still a diplomatic purging of that kind of presence in embassies 
around the world: Australia's been no exception. But I repeat, 
we don't want to make any kind of major issue of this with the 
Russian Government, they are very cooperative. Once it was drawn 
to their attention as a result of the ASIO investigation that 
some inappropriate activities were occurring, then the issue was 
responsibly and satisfactorily resolved. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

