<F P=100> Cambodia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hun Sen on Pressure on KR; Seeks Dutch Aid </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2402044094 Phnom Penh National Radio of Cambodia Network 
in Cambodian 0200 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2402044094 </F>
<F P=104>  Phnom Penh National Radio of Cambodia Network 
in Cambodian 0200 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Cambodian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Second Prime Minister Samdech Hun Sen told Mr. 
Georges Albert Wehry, ambassador of the Netherlands to Cambodia 
[name and title as heard], on the morning of 22 February that 
the current military campaign against the Khmer Rouge [KR] 
ordered by him and Prince Krompreah Norodom Ranariddh is not a 
solution to the problem, but pressure on the guerrillas to come 
to the negotiating table. 
  Answering a request from the Netherlands, Samdech Hun Sen 
said troop reduction cannot now be implemented in Cambodia 
because of three essential factors: First, the reduction can 
affect political problems; second, the royal government still 
needs Armed Forces for self-defense and to counterattack the KR, 
preventing them from further causing insecurity among the 
people; third, the government has not yet provided those troops 
with any skill or possibility to earn a living after the troop 
cut. 
  Samdech Hun Sen reaffirmed that only peaceful political 
means 
can solve the KR conflict, not military offensives. He also 
said that the security situation and the KR problem are not 
obstacles to the Netherlands' investment in Cambodia or the 
Netherlands' aid to the country. He urged investors to do 
business in Cambodia since the country abounds with manpower, 
and he called on the Netherlands to help promote Cambodia's 
agricultural sector. 
  Mr. Georges Albert Wehry informed Samdech Hun Sen that at 
present the Netherlands is exploring how it can help Cambodia 
and determine what its needs are. The Netherlands already 
granted $1.5 million in aid to Cambodia [words indistinct]. 

</TEXT>

