<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Remarks by Japan's Hata on Nuclear Issue Decried </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2402045794 Pyongyang KCNA in English 0442 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2402045794 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Unreasonable Act" -- KCNA headline] </F>
  [Text] Pyongyang, February 24 (KCNA) -- Japanese Foreign 
Minister Tsutomu Hata and some Western figures argue that the 
nuclear inspection recently agreed upon between the Democratic 
People's Republic of Korea and the International Atomic Energy 
Agency [IAEA] does not mean "solution of the nuclear dispute" on 
the Korean peninsula. They claim that "a special inspection of 
two military sites must be made". Commenting on this, an 
analyst of MINJU CHOSON today says: What Hata said is a very 
unreasonable balderdash intended to put a brake on the 
implementation of the agreement reached between the DPRK and the 
IAEA with much difficulty after repeated negotiations. 
  The inspection agreed upon this time is not routine and ad 
hoc inspections pursuant to the safeguards agreement but an 
inspection under the special situation in which the DPRK 
temporarily suspended the effectuation of its withdrawal from 
the Nuclear Non- Proliferation Treaty. 
  We do not think that the foreign minister of a country put 
his nose into our inspection issue, not knowing this. 
  Hata's claim for "special inspection of two military sites" 
reveals his sinister intention to spoil the agreement on 
inspection for guaranteeing the continuity of safeguards which 
was reached with much difficulty and force a "special 
inspection" upon us at any cost. 
  His rigmarole is nothing but a petty trick to divert 
elsewhere the attention of the world from Japan's nuclear 
armament by obstructing the solution to our nuclear issue and 
aggravating the relations between the DPRK and the IAEA and 
between the DPRK and the United States. 
  We warn that Japanese Foreign Minister Hata and his likes 
must act with discretion, clearly knowing what the "special 
inspection" means and what consequences it will entail. 

</TEXT>

