<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Parties Support 31 Jan Statement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2302233094 Pyongyang KCNA in English 2228 GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2302233094 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, February 23 (KCNA) -- Political parties 
and organisations of various countries expressed full support to 
the January 31 statement of a spokesman for the Foreign Ministry 
of the DPRK denouncing the perfidy of the United States in 
reversing all points of agreement and promises between it and 
the DPRK. 
  Joint statements were published by the Danish Workers' 
Party, 
Common Cause, the Communist Party of Denmark (Marxist-Leninist) 
and the Communist Party of Denmark on February 10, by the 
Central Committee of the Bulgarian Communist Party (Marxists) 
and the Left-Wing Alliance of Bulgaria on February 3 and by the 
People's Democratic Movement of Guyana, the Amerindian Action 
Movement of Guyana, the Guyana Committee for Support of Korea's 
Reunification and the Guyana-Korea Friendship Association on 
February 2. 
  Statements were also released by the National Committee of 
the Workers' Party of Zaire, the Central Committee of the 
October 8 Revolutionary Movement of Brazil, the Asian Regional 
Institute of the Chuche Idea, the Nepal-Korea Friendship 
Association and the Union of Tanzania Workers. 
  The statements denounced the aggressive moves of the United 
States in violating the sovereignty of the DPRK. 
  They noted that the United States which is responsible for 
the origin of the nuclear issue on the Korean peninsula must not 
try to solve the issue from the position of strength but 
affirmatively respond to the formula of package solution 
proposed by the DPRK for a fair solution to the nuclear issue in 
the spirit of the DPRK-U.S. joint statement. 
  Pointing out that it is a mistake to try to stifle the DPRK 
with strength, the statements urged the United States to act 
with discretion. 
  H.G. Mahundi, police superintendent of the Ministry of Home 
Affairs of Tanzania, in a statement released on February 7 said 
that the "nuclear issue" of Korea could not be solved by a 
strong arm or strength and demanded that the United States 
correct its wrong stand, abide by the agreed points and respond 
to the DPRK-U.S. talks before it is too late. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

