<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Leaders Support Korean `Just Cause' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2402050494 Pyongyang KCNA in English 0433 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2402050494 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, February 24 (KCNA) -- Party and state 
leaders of various countries voiced support to the just cause of 
the Korean people. 
  Ugandan President Yoweri Kaguta Museveni, when he received a 
delegation of the Workers' Party of Korea (WPK) headed by Yi 
Chi-su, president of the Chuche Idea Academy, expressed full 
support to the WPK's stand toward the reunification question and 
the nuclear issue on the Korean peninsula. He expressed the 
hope that the relations between the Uganda National Resistance 
Movement and the WPK would be consolidated and developed further 
still. Inaan Raad, chairman of the Nationalist Socialist Party 
of Syria in Lebanon, when he received the DPRK ambassador to 
Lebanon, expressed firm support and solidarity for the Workers' 
Party and people of Korea in their struggle to defend the 
sovereignty of the country and dignity of the nation. 
  The just struggle of the Korean people is a struggle to 
defend the interests of the peaceloving peoples of the world 
including the Arab people, he added. 
  Pointing out that the "nuclear issue" of Korea is a product 
of the anti-DPRK moves of the United States, he stressed: "The 
U.S. must stop the nuclear threat as agreed upon in the 
DPRK-U.S. joint statement and take a sincere stand to solve the 
nuclear issue on the Korean peninsula by means of negotiation, 
not by pressure." 
  Mohamedoun Dicko, secretary general of the Executive 
Committee of the African Party for the Solidarity and Justice of 
Mali, when he received the DPRK ambassador, said that his 
party's support to the lines and policies of the Workers' Party 
of Korea would be invariable in the future. 
  He expressed the conviction that Korea would certainly be 
reunified in the form of confederation clarified by the great 
leader his excellency President Kim Il-song. "It is the wisest 
way to solve the nuclear issue on the Korean peninsula through 
the DPRK-U.S. talks," he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

