<F P=100> Thailand </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tour Agency Cites Unfair Treatment in Laos </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2302131594 Bangkok PHUCHATKAN in Thai 23 Feb 94 p 6 </F>
<F P=103> BK2302131594 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok PHUCHATKAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Thai </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Nakhon Phanom Province Governor Sucharit Patchimnan 
disclosed that he had received a letter from the United Tour 
Company about the difficulties and inconveniences it encountered 
in organizing a package tour to Thakhek Township in Khammouane 
Province, Laos. Sucharit said he had contacted Khammouane 
Province Governor Inpong Sai-gnavong for clarification on this 
issue. 
  The Thai-owned United Tour Company cited many 
inconveniences, 
including the collection of border passage fees by the Lao 
authorities and the intended monopolization of the tourism 
industry in the Lao province. 
  The governor of Nakhon Phanom Province said that the 
provincial authority, together with the provincial Tourism 
Office, are trying to solve the problem in such a way that 
relations between the two countries will not be affected. Laos 
is in the process of changing many policies, and new regulations 
might be adopted. 
  Phairot Prokkaeo, director of Nakhon Phanom Province's 
Tourism Office, said that this is the first complaint about 
unfair treatment of Thai tour agencies by the Lao authorities. 
His office is waiting for more information from the Lao side. 
The solution to the problem might require joint efforts by the 
governors of the two neighboring provinces. Considering the 
nature of the problem, there could be some misunderstanding 
between the United Tour Company and the Lao authorities. 
  A tourist industry source in Nakhon Phanom Province revealed 
that two tour agencies -- namely Siphanom Tour and United Tour 
Companies -- are operating in the province, while the governor 
of Khammouane Province plans to set up a provincial tour agency 
to be officially called the Khammouane Tourism Company. The two 
Thai companies will be required to maintain regular contact with 
the Lao company in sending tourists to Khammouane Province. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

