<H3> <TI>   DPRK Reportedly To Allow IAEA Observers 1 Mar </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2302143494 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 1400 GMT 23 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK2302143494 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Cha Man-sun from Vienna] </F>
  [Text] North Korea notified the U.S. side that it will 
allow the International Atomic Energy Agency's [IAEA] inspection 
team to enter North Korea from 1 March. At the U.S.-North Korea 
contact held on 22 February in New York, North Korea notified 
the U.S. side that it will allow the IAEA's inspection team to 
enter North Korea so that it can start inspections from 1 March. 
  Councillor Yun Ho-chin who is participating in the IAEA 
Board 
of Governor's meeting as the North Korean representative, said 
that because the United States put forth the practical 
implementation of the exchange of special envoys of the 
South-North as a condition, no agreement has been reached 
regarding this kind of schedule. He added that the entry of the 
inspection team can be delayed depending on the attitude of the 
United States. 

