<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Seoul Said To Offer Contact if DPRK Issues Visas </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2402032394 Seoul YONHAP in English 0306 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2402032394 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Feb. 24 (YONHAP) -- The South Korean 
Government will propose to North Korea that a working-level 
meeting be held on exchanging special envoys if Pyongyang issues 
visas to International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) inspectors on 
Friday. 
  The decision was made as Pyongyang expressed hope that Seoul 
would take the initiative in resuming inter-Korean dialogue at 
working-level meetings with the United States in New York on 
Wednesday and Thursday, informed sources said. 
  If North Korea and the United States reach agreement at 
their 
meeting on Friday, Prime Minister Yi Hoe-chang will call a high- 
level strategic meeting to prepare a telephone message to his 
North Korean counterpart offering to hold the fourth 
working-level meeting on exchanging special envoys. 
  The message under consideration is expected to call for a 
working-level contact on the southern side of the truce village 
of Panmunjom early next month. 
  In line with the working-level meeting, informed sources 
said, Seoul will reportedly announce suspension of the annual 
South Korea- U.S. military exercise "Team Spirit" provided that 
North Korea cooperates fully with International Atomic Energy 
Agency (IAEA) inspection activities and shows sincerity toward 
inter-Korean dialouge. 
  Pyongyang and Washington met again in New York on Thursday 
to 
continue discussions on follow-up measures to North Korea's 
acceptance of IAEA inspections. 
  The two are said to be near a compromise and may announce a 
set of agreements after meeting on Friday. 

</TEXT>

