<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government May Relax Business Travel To North </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2102020694 Seoul YONHAP in English 0142 GMT 21 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2102020694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Feb. 21 (YONHAP) -- The government plans to 
ease restrictions on visits to North Korea by South Korean 
businessmen in view of recent developments in the North Korean 
nuclear issue, officials said Monday. The government would also 
relax regulations for South Korean businessmen wishing to set up 
pilot business ventures in North Korea if the nuclear problem 
was resolved, they said. 
  Seoul is studying a revision of its stance on inter-Korean 
economic cooperation to allow business contacts "when 
South-North dialogue makes significant progress." Until now, it 
had maintained it would allow inter-Korean business contacts 
only "when a breakthrough in the nuclear issue was found." The 
new government policy would represent a considerable relaxation 
on other pre-conditions that call for Pyongyang's return to the 
Nuclear Non- proliferation Treaty, acceptance of the 
International Atomic Energy Agency's [IAEA] ad hoc and special 
inspections, an inter-Korean agreement on simultaneous 
inspections of each other's nuclear facilities and reactivation 
of the South-North joint nuclear commission. 
  In addition, the government plans to relax conditions for 
South Korean businesses to establish small, pilot ventures in 
North Korea. Seoul had said it would only approve such ventures 
after the two Koreas conducted mutual inspections of their 
nuclear facilities and Pyongyang accepted special inspections by 
the IAEA. 
  The proposed changes are being contemplated to actively 
promote economic cooperation with Pyongyang while maintaining 
Seoul's original policy of linking inter-Korean economic 
cooperation with the nuclear issue. If the current government 
policy was maintained, it is possible that inter-Korean economic 
cooperation would be delayed considerably, one official said. 
"The government has decided to apply its economic cooperation 
policy flexibly while watching North Korea's attitude closely," 
he said, asking for anonymity. 
  The official stressed, however, that the government would 
not 
separate the economic and nuclear issues because South Korea was 
committed to going along with its allies on the nuclear problem. 
Overall economic cooperation with North Korea could be possible 
only after suspicions about North Korea's nuclear intentions 
were cleared up, he added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

