<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Institute Claims Farm Products Safer Than Imports </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2402082194 Seoul YONHAP in English 0730 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2402082194 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Feb. 24 (YONHAP) -- South Korean farm 
products contain fewer pesticides than imports and are thus much 
safer, according to the Rural Development Administration's 
Agricultural Chemicals Research Institute. Tests conducted on 
840 samples of 11 farm products including rice, apples, 
strawberries, cucumbers and pears from 1990 to 1992 revealed 
that 55 percent of the samples contained farm chemicals in 
amounts below the permissible levels, the institute announced on 
Thursday. No organic chlorine-series chemicals causing chronic 
poisoning were found in the rice samples produced in 1990, while 
organic phosphorus- and carbamate-series chemicals, which are 
easily digested by the human body, were detected in amounts 
below the permissible levels. 
  In 1992, the U.S. Food and Drug Administration detected, in 
tests of 5,816 samples of grain, fruit and vegetables produced 
in the United States, chemicals in 36.8 percent of the samples, 
with the chemicals in 1.2 percent being in amounts above 
permissible levels. 
  The institute's director, Yi Kun-chong, said Korean 
agricultural products were healthy because of farmers' 
observance of standards for safe use of pesticides established 
in 1980. In Korea, no pesticides are applied to farm products 
after they are harvested, while some foreign countries use 
chemicals on their farm products after the harvest to prevent 
decomposition or keep them pest-free during storage or shipment 
for export. Yi said his institute would strive to develop safer 
agricultural chemicals for safer farm products. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

