<H3> <TI>   Agreement With PRC on Preventing Double Taxation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2402115194 Seoul YONHAP in English 1007 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2402115194 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Feb. 24 (YONHAP) -- South Korea and China 
have completely agreed on the conclusion of a bilateral double 
taxation prevention agreement, which was initialed in Beijing on 
Thursday. A Finance Ministry official said the agreement will be 
formally signed during President Kim Yong-sam's official visit 
to China toward the close of next month. 
  The agreement, consisting of 29 articles and a memorandum, 
will, among other things, allow South Korean industries active 
in China at least the same treatment as accorded to Chinese 
industries in terms of taxation. The agreement is expected to go 
into force late this year after being ratified by the National 
Assembly. The accord was initialed by Om Nak-yong, a Finance 
Ministry director, and Zhang Xanghai, deputy director of China's 
State Administration of Taxation, following their final-round 
negotiations since Feb. 20, the official said. 

</TEXT>

