<H3> <TI>   Telecommunications Pact Signed With Mexico </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2402021994 Seoul YONHAP in English 0157 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2402021994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Feb. 24 (YONHAP) -- The trade imbalance, 
anti-dumping suits and import barriers were discussed at a South 
Korea-Mexico joint committee session in Mexico City this week, 
the first round since the North American Free Trade Agreement 
(NAFTA) took effect this year, the Foreign Ministry said 
Thursday. Mexican officials voiced concern over the growing 
trade imbalance in Seoul's favor and requested that South Korea 
lift restrictions on importing Mexican liquor, poultry and 
fruit, ministry officials said. 
  Seoul raised the issue of the growing number of anti-dumping 
investigations into Korean products in Mexico and asked for 
assurance that the probes be unbiased. It also brought up 
Mexican limits on quota imports and its customs tariffication 
system, naming them as trade barriers. 
  South Korea pressed Mexico to reach early conclusion of an 
investment protection accord to activate bilateral investment 
activities but the Mexicans reacted negatively, officials said. 
  The two countries initialed a telecommunications cooperation 
pact and agreed to hold talks in the near future while 
scheduling maritime negotiations for mid-March. 

</TEXT>

