<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Governing Bodies Found To Misappropriate Funds </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2402080594 Seoul YONHAP in English 0550 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2402080594 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Feb. 24 (YONHAP) -- The Home Affairs 
Ministry, investigating misappropriation of charity funds by 
local autonomous governing bodies and central government 
agencies, disclosed Thursday that more of such cases exist than 
was previously known. 
  The Ministry said that many local autonomous governing 
bodies 
besides the six cities and counties in Kyonggi Province, in 
which misappropriation cases had already been revealed by the 
Board of Audit and Inspection (BAI), used charity funds 
contributed by the public for other purposes between 1991 and 
1993. The BAI announced Tuesday that heads of central government 
agencies and local autonomous governing bodies had used charity 
funds intended for the poor as "confidential expenses" or for 
other reasons. 
  The Home Ministry has decided to begin a full-fledged 
investigation into 46 government agencies and local autonomous 
bodies in which the Board of Audit and Inspection has already 
exposed scandals. The Ministry is also studying ways to expand 
inspection by the BAI to include 275 local autonomous governing 
bodies, citing the principle of equity. It plans to rebuke 
public servants found guilty of committing irregularities and 
misappropriating charity funds who are uncovered by the BAI. 

</TEXT>

