<H3> <TI>   Companies Vie for Stake in Mobile Phone Project </TI></H3>
<H4>   FKI Chief Delays PRC Visit </H4>
<F P=102> SK2202084894 Seoul YONHAP in English 0737 GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2202084894 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Feb. 22 (YONHAP) -- The head of the 
Federation of Korean Industries (FKI), Choe Chong-hyon, has 
postponed plans to visit China this week, in his capacity as 
Sungkyong Group chairman, until the end of next month, 
apparently because selection of the controlling shareholder in 
the nation's second cellular phone company is not going well. 
  The Sunkyong Group announced on Tuesday that chairman Choe's 
planned visit to China from Feb. 24 to March 1 at the invitation 
of a Chinese oil-refining organization had been put off until 
the end of March because of problems with his itinerary. 
  The FKI has changed the dates for two leadership meetings on 
selection of the main shareholder of the second mobile 
telecommunications firm from Feb. 21 and 25 to Feb. 22 and 23, 
due to chairman Choe's plans to visit China. 
  Business sources said Choe probably postponed his visit 
because Pohang Iron and Steel Co. chairman Chong Myong-sik and 
Kolon Group chairman Yi Tong-chan had failed to agree on who 
should own the second cellular phone firm at a meeting on 
Sunday. Chong and Yi are vying for the phone business. 
  Choe made his decision on Monday. 

</TEXT>

