<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Companies Vie for Stake in Mobile Phone Project </TI></H3>
<H4>   FKI Chief Tries Mediation </H4>
<F P=102> SK2402060994 Seoul YONHAP in English 0538 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2402060994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Feb. 24 (YONHAP) -- The Federation of Korean 
Industries (FKI) board held a closed meeting Wednesday night at 
which Kim Sok-won, chairman of the Ssangyong Business Group, 
reported on his meetings with Chong Myong-sik and Yi Tong-chan, 
respective chairmen of Pohang Iron and Steel Co. [POSCO] and 
Kolon Group, which are vying to take the majority stake in the 
consortium for the second mobile telephone project, FKI Vice 
Chairman Cho Kyu- ha said Thursday. 
  Kim reportedly met with the two chairmen to hammer out an 
agreement between the uncompromising business groups in their 
fight for control of the lucrative business. 
  FKI was authorized by the Communications Ministry late last 
year to form a single consortium for the second cellular phone 
network by this month. 
  The cut-throat competition was narrowed down to consortiums 
led by POSCO and Kolon after FKI Chairman Choe Chong-hyon's 
Sunkyong Group dropped out of the race, aiming instead to become 
the major stockholder of Korea Mobile Telecom, a state-run 
monopoly that is to be privatized. 
  FKI will conduct a final screening and comparative study 
before announcing the majority stockholder and participating 
local and foreign companies on Feb. 28, Cho said. 

</TEXT>

