<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Appeal Planned to G-7 on Exchange Rate Movement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2302101494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0955 GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2302101494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 23 KYODO -- Finance Minister Hirohisa 
Fujii said Wednesday [23 February] he would appeal to his Group 
of Seven (G-7) partners to help avoid volatile exchange rate 
movements like the yen's recent advance against the dollar. 
"Rapid swings of exchange rates are a minus not only for Japan 
but also for the global economy, and I will explain this at the 
G-7 meeting," Fujii told the House of Representatives' Budget 
Committee. 
  Finance ministers and central bankers from the G-7 
industrial 
nations are to meet in Frankfurt on Saturday. 
  Asked by an opposition lawmaker about a planned income tax 
cut for fiscal 1994, Fujii indicated that an income tax cut will 
be carried out in the following years as well. "It seems that 
the income tax cut has been misunderstood as one for a single 
year only," Fujii said. 

</TEXT>

