<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   To `Brief' Nations on Tax Issue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2402141394 Tokyo KYODO in English 1223 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2402141394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 24 KYODO -- Japan will seek support 
for a stable yen and its economic measures at a Group of Seven 
(G-7) meeting in Germany this weekend, an international 
financial source said Thursday [24 February]. 
  Finance ministers and central bankers of the G-7 nations 
will 
gather on Saturday in Kronberg, the outskirts of Frankfurt, to 
reaffirm cooperation in macroeconomic measures for global 
growth, stable currency rates and aid to Russia, the source 
said. The G-7 nations are Britain, Canada, France, Germany, 
Italy, Japan and the United States. 
  On the exchange rates, Japan will explain that the yen's 
sharp rise since early last year has "poured water" on signs of 
economic recovery, he said. Since then, Japan has launched a 
spate of pump-priming measures, including the latest record 
15.25 trillion yen package, despite the tough financial 
situation, the source noted. 
  Japan will stress the plan's inclusion of tax cuts worth 6 
trillion yen to stimulate consumption and deregulatory actions 
primarily to facilitate land-market liquidity, the source said. 
He said such steps were taken while continuing to boost public 
works and housing-related loans, sectors that remain strong. 
  Japan will brief other nations particularly on the tax issue 
to win support, the source said, citing U.S. criticism over the 
effects of a single-year tax cut. 
  U.S. officials have said such cuts are not enough to prop up 
the economy and reduce trade imbalance. They were disappointed 
with the scrapping of Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa's 
original plan. 
  It called for a permanent 6 trillion yen tax cut and an 
offsetting 7 percent "welfare tax" in three years to replace the 
3 percent consumption tax. The U.S. side had pictured tax cuts 
worth 18 trillion yen in three years. 
  The source emphasized that Japan's ruling coalition leaders 
agreed to conduct a full-fledged tax reform by year's end, an 
accord that won confirmation at a cabinet meeting. 
  He noted that the G-7 ministers and central bankers are 
unlikely to issue a joint statement on macroeconomic policies 
and currency rates, but there are chances for the aid to Russia. 
Discussions on macroeconomic policies and exchange rates will 
be limited to the morning session of the one-day meeting that 
kicks off at around 11 A.M., he said. 
  With each nation presenting its economic measures, there 
will 
not be much to discuss, he said, indicating pressure on a single 
nation is unlikely. 
  The ministers and central bankers will focus on Russian aid 
in the afternoon session and Russian counterparts will join for 
about an hour before the meeting ends at around 5 P.M., the 
source said. The G-7 nations want to directly confirm economic 
reforms since Russian President Boris Yeltsin formed a new 
cabinet in the wake of elections last December, he said. 
  According to latest information, the source said the new 
cabinet intends to inherit and continue reforms led by 
inflation-curbing economic policies that are the key condition 
for multilateral aid from G-7 nations. 
  Large chunks of aid through the International Monetary Fund 
and the World Bank have not been implemented due to Russia's 
political and economic uncertainties. 
  The source said the aid package decided at a G-7 meeting of 
finance and foreign ministers last April in Tokyo and upgraded 
in a Tokyo summit last July is unlikely to be increased or 
changed. 
  Confirming that Russian policies are in line with the aid 
conditions will be the major issue, he noted. 
  Despite his indication that the aid will be the major topic, 
global attention is apparently fixed on currency and trade 
issues between Japan and the U.S. 
  Bilateral trade disputes have escalated since Japan flatly 
rejected a U.S. demand for "numerical targets" at a meeting 
between Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa and President Bill 
Clinton in Washington on February 11. After trade talks failed, 
the yen surged more than 6 yen against the dollar on speculation 
over the U.S. tolerating a stronger yen. 
  Japan and the U.S. are now in a "cooling off" period and the 
G-7 meeting will be the first top-level one since the summit. 
Japanese officials said a possible meeting between Finance 
Minister Hirohisa Fujii and U.S. Treasury Secretary Lloyd 
Bentsen has not been scheduled. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

