<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Takemura on Plan for New Market-Opening Package </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2402034894 Tokyo KYODO in English 0328 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2402034894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 24 KYODO -- The government hopes to 
swiftly work out a fresh package of measures to open Japan's 
markets more to foreign competition, Chief Cabinet Secretary 
Masayoshi Takemura said Thursday [24 February]. But the top 
government spokesman said a meeting of cabinet ministers to be 
held Friday will not reach any conclusion on specific 
market-opening measures. 
  "The cabinet-level meeting will be held to try to map out a 
plan as early as possible," Takemura told a news conference. 
The meeting, bringing together nine ministers, including the 
foreign, finance and international trade ministers, will take 
place after a regular cabinet meeting Friday morning, he said. 
  It will aim to formulate a program to speed up deregulation, 
strengthen import and investment promotion steps, revamp 
competition policy and improve government procurement processes. 
  Last week, Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa and 
subcabinet-level officials who represented Japan in trade 
negotiations with the U.S. agreed to map out a four-pronged 
scheme as soon as possible. The move is intended to stave off 
the trade dispute with the U.S., which has been increasing 
pressure on Japan to whittle down its lopsided trade surplus 
since the collapse of talks on a bilateral trade framework on 
February 11. 
  Meanwhile, Takemura indicated Japan will consider an 
extension of planned tax cuts beyond this year after 
implementing a sweeping tax system reform. 
  Under the original plan, the tax cut period is limited to 
only this year. This has sparked U.S. criticism that the tax 
cut is far from sufficient to stimulate the languishing Japanese 
economy. 

</TEXT>

