<H3> <TI>   `Top-Ranking Official' Opposes Trade Targets </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2402112894 Tokyo KYODO in English 1117 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2402112894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 24 KYODO -- A top-ranking official of 
the Foreign Ministry said Thursday [24 February] he is opposed 
to setting any numerical target to reduce Japan's huge trade 
surplus. 
  The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, argued 
there could be no figure (for such a target) that Japan could 
attain and satisfy the United States at the same time. His 
remarks were in response to a comment made in the business 
community to propose to the U.S. as an "objective criteria" a 
target of setting a ratio of Japan's current-account surplus to 
its gross domestic product (GDP). 
  "Even if there should be target figures which can satisfy 
the 
U.S. Administration, (setting such targets) would only serve as 
a stopgap measure. In a couple of years, (U.S.-Japan relations) 
would get worse," he said. 

</TEXT>

