Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 24 KYODO -- Japan must take drastic 
action to improve its strained economic relations with the 
United States, a top Trade Ministry official said Thursday [24 
February]. The official at the Ministry of International Trade 
and Industry (MITI), speaking on condition of anonymity, said 
some Japanese officials do not understand the seriousness of 
U.S. discontent over Japan's failure to meet Washington's 
demands. 
  He emphasized Japan should take strong measures to reduce 
its 
huge trade surplus by stimulating the economy and opening its 
auto market. 
  The official said the yen is staying where it is against the 
U.S. dollar on the foreign exchange market, only because of the 
Bank of Japan's intervention to support the dollar. He said the 
yen could rise sharply if the central bank stopped its selling 
of the yen. 

