<H3> <TI>   PRC's Zhu Rongji Continues Visit Activities </TI></H3>
<H4>   Seeks Help With GATT Membership </H4>
<F P=102> OW2402124194 Tokyo KYODO in English 1226 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2402124194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 24 KYODO -- China's Vice Premier Zhu 
Rongji sought Japan's support on Thursday [24 February] for its 
attempt to win membership of the General Agreement on Tariffs 
and Trade (GATT), officials said. Zhu made the request in a 
meeting with Yohei Kono, president of the opposition Liberal 
Democratic Party (LDP). 
  Kono replied that the LDP will actively support China's bid. 
  Zhu also asked for the LDP's support in Japan's expected 
provision of a fourth yen loan to China starting in fiscal 1996. 
  Zhu, currently on a nine-day visit to Japan which started 
Wednesday, also met three former prime ministers, Toshiki Kaifu, 
Noboru Takeshita and Kiichi Miyazawa. 
  Miyazawa, noting the need of stepping up Japan's support of 
the Chinese economy, expressed concern over China's potential to 
become a military superpower, the officials said. 
  "If China becomes economically strong, it will be also 
militarily strong. Japan has a policy of not becoming a 
military superpower, so I also want China not to be one," 
Miyazawa was quoted as saying. 
  Zhu, calling Miyazawa's concern "groundless," replied that 
"China will never seek hegemony." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-30001 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas037_a_94009" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-037 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  24 February 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   PRC's Zhu Rongji Continues Visit Activities </TI></H3>
<H4>   Discusses DPRK Nuclear Issue </H4>
<F P=102> OW2402121394 Tokyo KYODO in English 1135 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2402121394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 24 KYODO -- Japan and China agreed 
Thursday that Japanese Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa will 
visit China between March 19 and 21 for talks with Chinese 
leaders, Foreign Ministry officials said. Hosokawa and Chinese 
Vice Premier Zhu Rongji reached the accord in a meeting at the 
prime minister's official residence, the officials said. 
  Details of Hosokawa's itinerary will be further worked out 
by 
the two governments, they said. 
  Zhu conveyed messages from Chinese President and Communist 
Party Leader Jiang Zemin and Premier Li Peng saying they are 
looking forward to meeting Hosokawa in Beijing in March, the 
officials said. 
  Hosokawa replied that he looks forward to the trip, they 
said. 
  During the 50-minute meeting, Hosokawa called for China's 
continued role in persuading North Korea to accept international 
inspections of its suspected nuclear weapons development sites, 
the officials said. 
  Hosokawa told Zhu that Pyongyang should further accept 
special inspections by the International Atomic Energy Agency 
(IAEA) and implement an accord with South Korea to denuclearize 
the Korean peninsula. 
  Zhu, currently on a nine-day visit to Japan starting 
Wednesday, was quoted as saying there have been developments 
recently concerning North Korea's suspected nuclear problem and 
that China intends to extend efforts within its capacity. 
  Hosokawa gave high marks to China's efforts to promote 
reform 
and open-door policies and added Japan will continue to support 
such efforts, the officials said. 
  Zhu predicted that mutual economic interdependence between 
China and Japan will further strengthen, noting that trade 
between the two amounted to 39 billion dollars last year, up 54 
percent from the previous year. 
  The vice premier also noted that Japan is now China's top 
trading partner exceeding Hong Kong, while China is Japan's 
second biggest trading partner. Zhu was quoted as saying the 
two nations should further promote economic exchanges. 
  Hosokawa voiced support for China's bid to become a member 
of 
the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT), the officials 
said. 
  Zhu told Hosokawa that China has been making various efforts 
to become a GATT member, lowering duties and improving 
transparency of its legislation. He handed Premier Li's letter 
to Hosokawa which asked for Tokyo's continued cooperation in 
China's bid to enter the world trade body. 
  Foreign Ministry officials said Beijing has apparently been 
sending similar letters to other major countries as well. 
  Hosokawa told the Chinese that Japan is interested in 
China's 
environmental preservation and military expenses. The prime 
minister cited Japanese guidelines in extending official 
development assistance (ODA) which takes note of such fields. 
  Zhu told Hosokawa that China has been making various efforts 
to preserve the environment including beefing up legislation, 
they said. 
  The vice premier noted China's military expenses in 1993 
were 
43.7 million yuan (about 655 million yen), about 1 percent of 
its gross national product (GNP). He said the military expenses 
are mostly used for defensive purposes and that the expenditure 
is limited to the minimum necessary to defend its population of 
1.2 billion. 
  Zhu told Hosokawa he does not think it appropriate to link 
China's human rights record to the "most-favored-nation" trade 
status in the United States. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

