<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   PRC's Zhu Rongji Continues Visit Activities </TI></H3>
<H4>   Seeks Help With Bank of China </H4>
<F P=102> OW2402023094 Tokyo KYODO in English 0202 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2402023094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 24 KYODO -- Chinese Vice Premier Zhu 
Rongji asked the Bank of Japan (BOJ) on Thursday [24 February] 
to continue cooperating to beef up the functions of the People's 
Bank of China, officials of the central bank said. Zhu, who 
arrived in Tokyo Wednesday for a nine-day visit to Japan, made 
the request during morning talks with BOJ Governor Yasushi Mieno 
at a Tokyo hotel. 
  The chief economic planner of China as head of the central 
bank briefed Mieno on Beijing's efforts to shift to a "socialist 
market economy," the officials said. 
  The officials did not reveal the details of the Mieno-Zhu 
talks, but Zhu is believed to have clarified his bank's policy 
of keeping a tight grip on credit, at least for the time being, 
to calm an overheating Chinese economy. 
  Mieno reportedly told Zhu the Japanese central bank will 
continue to support China's attempt to shift to a market-driven 
economy. 

</TEXT>

