<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   PRC's Zhu Rongji Continues Visit Activities </TI></H3>
<H4>   Meets With Foreign Minister Hata </H4>
<F P=102> OW2402144294 Tokyo KYODO in English 1423 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2402144294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 24 KYODO -- Foreign Minister Tsutomu 
Hata urged China to take "tangible measures" to clear obstacles 
in winning "most favored nation (MFN)" trade status by the 
United States, Foreign Ministry officials said Thursday. Hata 
told Vice Premier Zhu Rongji that although Sino-U.S. ties seem 
to have improved recently, he thinks there are still some 
problems concerning renewal of the MFN status. 
  As one of the "tangible measures" to be taken to ensure 
renewal of the MFN status, Hata implied that Beijing should 
improve its human rights record, the officials said. 
  China's MFN status, which must be extended every year under 
U.S. law, ends in June. Washington has linked further extension 
this year to a "significant overall improvement" in China's 
human rights record. 
  Zhu told Hata that relations between Beijing and Washington 
have made progress since U.S. President Bill Clinton and Chinese 
President Jiang Zemin met in Seattle in November, the officials 
said. The meeting between Hata and Zhu lasted about 50 minutes 
and was followed by a dinner, they said. 
  Also during the meeting, Hata urged China to submit as early 
as possible official lists of projects to be covered by Japan's 
yen loans so that Tokyo and Beijing could determine the 
projects, the officials said. 
  He was quoted as saying Japan places importance on 
protecting 
the environment when extending loans. 
  When Hata visited China in early January, Japan and China 
agreed to divide Japan's loan periods from five years to 
three-year and two-year periods beginning with fiscal 1996 
starting April that year. 
  Beijing has sent unofficial lists to the Japanese Government 
of the projects to be handled under the yen loans but has yet to 
submit official lists, the officials said. 

</TEXT>

