<H3> <TI>   ROK Envoy Urges Cooperation on DPRK Issue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2402125494 Tokyo KYODO in English 1236 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2402125494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 24 KYODO -- South Korean Ambassador to 
Japan Kong No-myong said Thursday [24 February] that Japan and 
South Korea share the view that suspicion over North Korea's 
nuclear intentions should be put to rest by dialogue, with 
cooperation from the United States and China. 
  Kong, in an interview with KYODO NEWS SERVICE, said South 
Korea and Japan should maintain close cooperation in seeing that 
North Korea accepts adequate international inspections of its 
nuclear facilities to ensure against development of nuclear 
weapons. He said settlement of the matter should be made a 
precondition for consideration of North Korea's participation in 
regional organizations and activities, such as the Tumen River 
Development Project near the North Korea-China border and the 
Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum. 
  Kong said Tokyo and Seoul still face unresolved issues, such 
as addressing the suffering of so-called comfort women, who said 
they were forced by the Japanese Imperial Army to provide sex to 
soldiers during World War II. But he said South Koreans were 
very touched last year by Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa's 
apologies for Japan's war conduct and its colonization of the 
Korean peninsula. 
  President Kim is scheduled to visit Japan in late March. 

</TEXT>

