<H3> <TI>   Yokomichi Holds `Secret' Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2402000294 Tokyo KYODO in English 2324 GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2402000294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 24 KYODO -- A popular provincial 
governor is set to return to the national stage as a leading 
member of a planned new liberal party, sources in the ruling 
coalition said Thursday [24 February]. Takahiro Yokomichi, 
governor of Hokkaido in northern Japan, held secret talks with a 
cabinet minister Wednesday night on forming a new party that 
would involve a merger with the largest party in the coalition 
government, they said. 
  Yokomichi agreed in the meeting with Science and Technology 
Agency Chief Satsuki Eda to start preparations to form the new 
party with the Social Democratic Party (SDP) as its core, they 
said. Yokomichi, a former SDP member of the House of 
Representatives, told Eda, leader of the United Social 
Democratic Party, at the meeting in Tokyo that he is willing to 
run for a Diet seat in the next general election, they said. 
  He had already received a positive response to the idea of a 
new party from SDP Chairman Tomiichi Murayama and its secretary 
general, Wataru Kubo, the sources said. 
  Yokomichi met with Kubo and Chief Cabinet Secretary 
Masayoshi 
Takemura, leader of Sakigake (Harbinger), on February 12 and 
agreed to form a unified parliamentary group among the SDP, 
Sakigake and the Democratic Socialist Party, they said. 
Yokomichi, dubbed the "prince of the SDP," was elected to the 
Diet four times from 1969 and has been elected Hokkaido governor 
three times since 1983. 
  Shinseito and Komeito want a two-party system in which the 
seven coalition parties would merge into a single party, but the 
SDP and Sakigake prefer a moderate multiparty system. 
  Meanwhile, the ASAHI SHIMBUN reported Thursday that the SDP, 
the DSP and Sakigake have agreed to start regular consultations 
to strengthen ties among them. 

</TEXT>

