<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   SDP, DSP Reiterate Opposition to Reshuffle </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2402113794 Tokyo KYODO in English 1108 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2402113794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 24 KYODO -- Leaders of two out of seven 
ruling parties told Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa on Thursday 
[24 February] that an immediate cabinet reshuffle is not 
necessary, renewing their opposition to a shakeup expected to 
center on removing Chief Cabinet Secretary Masayoshi Takemura 
from his post, coalition sources said. In a meeting with 
Hosokawa, Social Democratic Party (SDP) Chairman Tomiichi 
Murayama and Democratic Socialist Party (DSP) Chairman Keigo 
Ouchi urged the premier to revoke his reshuffle plan, the 
officials said. 
  Hosokawa told the two that he may consider a reshuffle after 
the Diet passes both the third supplementary budget for fiscal 
1993 and an amendment to a political reform package, they said. 
The Diet passed the extra budget Wednesday, while the amendment 
is expected to be approved in early March. 
  From the coalition's seven parties, the SDP, DSP and 
Takemura's Sakigake (Harbinger) have objected to the reshaping 
plan while Shinseito (Japan renewal party) and Komeito [Clean 
Government Party] support it. 
  Takemura differs with Hosokawa on the blueprint for Japan's 
future politics. Hosokawa has reportedly considered seeking a 
two-party system called for by Shinseito and Komeito, but 
Takemura has voiced objections. 
  Takemura also attended the meeting and suggested he has not 
changed his position opposing his removal, the sources said. He 
has reportedly rejected Hosokawa's request to go to another 
ministerial post. 
  Murayama told Hosokawa that an immediate reshuffle will give 
"an impression of a power struggle" within the coalition. Ouchi 
asked the premier not to cause a crack in the coalition by a 
shakeup, they said. 
  Hosokawa was quoted as saying he does not have a concrete 
idea on a reshuffle and will decide on the matter after hearing 
opinions of ruling party leaders. 
  On Tuesday, Hosokawa told reporters he asked his top aides 
to 
look into the possibility of uniting seven ruling parties 
against the Liberal Democratic Party in the next general 
election for the House of Representatives. 
  The prime minister told leaders of the SDP, DSP and Sakigake 
that the idea of alliance has nothing to do with the merger of 
ruling parties nor with a two-party system. 

</TEXT>

