<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Coalition, LDP Agree on Reform Amendment </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2402071194 Tokyo KYODO in English 0702 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2402071194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 24 KYODO -- The ruling coalition 
parties and the opposition Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) agreed 
Thursday [24 February] on amendment of government-sponsored 
political reform bills, political sources said. The two sides 
are expected to jointly submit the amended package to the Diet 
on Monday and the bills are likely to be approved by the House 
of Representatives and the House of Councillors by Wednesday or 
later, they said. 
  The two camps struck a deal Thursday on the last remaining 
point of difference, when the coalition parties conceded to an 
LDP demand to discuss giving political parties the status of a 
juridical person, the sources said. 
  The LDP has called for the reform bills to state that 
political parties have the status of a juridical person, saying 
parties should be in a more responsible position because they 
will be subsidized by the government under the package. 
  The coalition has opposed this, maintaining that freedom of 
association under the Constitution may be violated if political 
parties are obliged to have a juridical person's status. 
  The two sides agreed to keep discussing the matter and 
conclude the debate by the time a bill on the locations of 300 
single-seat constituencies for the lower house is presented to 
the Diet, the sources said. The bill is expected to be 
presented in the fall. 
  According to the package, 300 lower house will be elected 
through a single-seat constituency system and the remaining 200 
through a proportional representation system. Currently, lower 
house members are elected from constituencies with two to six 
seats. 
  The package was passed January 29 at the last extraordinary 
session of the Diet, but some amendments and the date of 
enforcement were removed from the package to get it through. 
  Shortly before the passage, Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa 
and LDP President Yohei Kono agreed that the amendments and date 
of enforcement will be discussed at the current ordinary session. 

</TEXT>

