<F P=100> Vietnam </F>
<H3> <TI>   Phan Van Khai Assesses Banking Operations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2402100394 Hanoi Voice of Vietnam Network in Vietnamese 
2300 GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2402100394 </F>
<F P=104>  Hanoi Voice of Vietnam Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Vietnamese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Vietnam State Bank held a conference of 
governors of northern provinces' state banks and commercial 
banks in Hanoi yesterday. The purpose was to evaluate a drive 
to renovate banking inspection, control, and regulations over 
the past three years -- 1991-93 -- and to set forth tasks for 
1994-95. 
  Over the past three years, banking inspection, control, and 
regulations have been gradually brought into in line with 
renovation of the banking sector, ranging from special 
inspection and control drives to long-range supervision and 
on-the-spot large-scale inspection of credit organizations. 
This has contributed positively to restoring order and 
discipline in banking operations. 
  Addressing the conference, Deputy Prime Minister Phan Van 
Khai commended the sector for its efforts last year to contain 
and dispel inflation and gradually increase the value of 
Vietnamese currency. The sector's credit operations have 
gradually provided good service to various economic components. 
Financial settlement work has shown progress, resulting in an 
end to the shortage of cash. Many banks have had a surplus. 
  The deputy prime minister also pointed out major tasks to be 
carried out by the sector in 1994, which consist of formulating 
measures to stabilize the value of the Vietnamese currency; 
stepping up the mobilization of capital among the people and of 
foreign capital for economic components; managing foreign 
currency more satisfactorily; and reducing negativism and 
inconveniences if the banking sector is to meet various capital 
demands of the national economy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

