<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Denies Bentsen Hinted at 110-Yen Rate </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2402062294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0607 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2402062294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 24 KYODO -- A report of U.S. 
willingness to let the dollar rise to 110 yen is "completely 
misleading and warped," a senior Finance Ministry official said 
Thursday [24 February]. 
  Kosuke Nakahira, vice finance minister for international 
affairs, told a hastily called press conference that media 
reports' "reference to specific yen-rate levels are not a fact." 
He was referring to a report Thursday by the NIHON KEIZAI 
SHIMBUN about a discussion between U.S. Treasury Secretary Lloyd 
Bentsen and Japanese Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa at their 
meeting last month in Tokyo. 
  The major economic daily reported Bentsen as indicating the 
United States is willing to allow the dollar to rise to 110 yen. 
Nakahira said the report's "comments on exchange rates are 
completely misleading and warped," but he declined to disclose 
what Bentsen and Hosokawa actually discussed, saying, "they both 
agreed not to comment." 
  Asked if the yen's fall against the dollar is viewed as 
undesirable before the meeting of Group of Seven (G-7) finance 
ministers and central bankers Saturday in Germany, Nakahira 
said, "that's absolutely not in my mind." 
  Nakahira said he wants to scotch "as soon as possible rumors 
that do not reflect the facts." 
  Currency dealings are now conducted 24 hours a day, he 
noted, 
when asked about the timing of the press conference during Tokyo 
trading hours. 
  Nakahira also rejected suggestions of pressure from the 
United States, saying, "we are in close contact every day." 
  He also said he wants to make it clear that monetary 
authorities do not "guide or tolerate exchange rates." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

