<F P=100> SOUTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Singapore </F>
<H3> <TI>   Joint Naval Exercise With Indian Navy Begins </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2402103594 Singapore THE STRAITS TIMES in English 24 Feb 
94 p 18 </F>

<F P=103> BK2402103594 </F>
<F P=104>  Singapore THE STRAITS TIMES </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ships from the Indian Navy and the Republic of 
Singapore Navy (RSN) have begun a week-long naval exercise in 
the Indian Ocean. Two RSN missile corvettes and an Indian Navy 
submarine will take part in the exercise involving 
anti-submarine warfare manoeuvres. The exercise will continue 
until Sunday. 
  A Mindef [Ministry of Defense] statement issued on Tuesday 
said the exercise was designed to "promote professional 
interaction and to enhance bilateral ties between the two 
navies". About 350 officers and men from the two navies will 
take part in this second joint naval exercise. The first one 
was also held in the Indian Ocean in February last year. The two 
RSN missile corvettes, the RSS Victory and RSS Valour, left for 
the exercise on Friday. The commander of the RSN task group is 
Lt-Colonel Gary Lee, who is also commander of the RSN's 188 
Squadron. 
  The two vessels arrived at Port Blair in the South Andaman 
Islands on Sunday and participants spent Sunday and Monday in 
familiarisation and shore training before sailing for the waters 
around the Andaman and Nicobar islands for the exercise. 
  The Mindef statement said the joint exercise between the RSN 
and the Indian Navy reflected the warm relationship between the 
two countries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

