<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hosokawa's 7 Mar Policy Speech to Diet Outlined </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2402142494 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 24 Feb 93 
Morning Edition p 1 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2402142494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The outline of Prime Minister Hosokawa's policy 
speech to the Diet was firmed up on 23 February. In the speech, 
Prime Minister Hosokawa will indicate that his government has 
entered its second term of "changes." Hosokawa will make clear 
his government will focus its efforts on "administrative reform" 
and "economic reform" -- the new major policy tasks following 
political reform. The prime minister also will announce his 
government is to put administrative reform at the top of its 
domestic agenda. He will express his eagerness to vigorously 
promote deregulation, decentralization, and the freedom of 
information. The government will submit a budget bill for 
fiscal 1994 to the Diet on 4 March for deliberation. Hosokawa 
is scheduled to deliver his policy speech to the Diet on 7 March. 
  The policy speech will also stress the achievements of the 
coalition government over the six months since it was 
inaugurated last August. These include the partial opening of 
the Japanese rice market, the enactment of political reform 
bills, and a package of stimulus measures which includes a cut 
in income tax. 
  Hosokawa will also unveil plans to: 1) Promote 
administrative reform, especially deregulation; 2) aid the 
recovery of the economy, open Japanese markets, and manage the 
economy and finance; 3) make sweeping changes of the current tax 
system to prepare for a society of senior citizens; and 4) make 
international contributions. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

