<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hosokawa, Watanabe Deny Reported 23 Feb Meeting </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2502060894 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 25 
Feb 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2502060894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 25 February Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] A news report on 24 February sent off shock waves 
in Nagata-cho [the political center of Japan, in Tokyo], already 
in upheaval over reports of a planned cabinet reshuffle and 
Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa's remarks on forming a unified 
parliamentary group for the ruling coalition parties. It was 
reported that Hosokawa and former Deputy Prime Minister and 
Foreign Minister Michio Watanabe, a Liberal Democratic Party 
[LDP] leader, had held a meeting on the evening of 23 February. 
Officials of the coalition parties as well as the LDP were sent 
rushing off to confirm the report. Could the prime minister 
have asked Watanabe to join the cabinet? Various speculations 
have made the rounds. Both the prime minister and Watanabe 
flatly denied that a meeting had been held, and refused to give 
any further comments. The truth about the "Hosokawa-Watanabe 
meeting" remains a mystery. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

